-- Article 39: External Hernias
-- Surgery 2 CME Content

-- Insert sections

INDIRECT INGUINAL HERNIA: Passes through deep inguinal ring, lateral to inferior epigastric vessels. Most common type in all ages and both sexes. Congenital (patent processus vaginalis) or acquired. May descend into scrotum. Covered by all three spermatic fasciae.

DIRECT INGUINAL HERNIA: Passes through Hesselbach triangle (posterior wall), medial to inferior epigastric vessels. Acquired, more common in elderly. Does not descend into scrotum. Less likely to strangulate due to wide neck.

HESSELBACH TRIANGLE: Medial border - rectus muscle; lateral border - inferior epigastric vessels; inferior border - inguinal ligament.

CLINICAL FEATURES: Groin swelling, cough impulse, reducibility. Differentiate from femoral hernia (below and lateral to pubic tubercle), varicocele, undescended testis, lymph nodes, lipoma of cord.'),
('d0000039-0000-0000-0000-000000000039'::uuid, 'content', 3, 'Other Abdominal Hernias', 'FEMORAL HERNIA: Through femoral canal, below and lateral to pubic tubercle. More common in women but inguinal still more common in women than femoral. High risk of strangulation due to narrow neck. Femoral ring boundaries: anterior (inguinal ligament), posterior (pectineal ligament), medial (lacunar ligament), lateral (femoral vein).

UMBILICAL HERNIA: Congenital (children) - most close spontaneously by age 2-4. Adult (para-umbilical) - acquired, more common in obese, multiparous women, ascites. May incarcerate omentum or bowel.

INCISIONAL HERNIA: Through previous surgical incision. Risk factors: wound infection, obesity, steroid use, malnutrition, midline vertical incisions, emergency surgery. Contains all layers except skin. May be large with loss of domain.

EPIGASTRIC HERNIA: Through linea alba above umbilicus. Contains preperitoneal fat, rarely bowel. Often multiple.

SPIGELIAN HERNIA: Through spigelian fascia at lateral border of rectus. Interparietal, often difficult to diagnose clinically. Ultrasound or CT helpful.'),
('d0000039-0000-0000-0000-000000000039'::uuid, 'content', 4, 'Surgical Management', 'GENERAL PRINCIPLES: Elective repair recommended for all symptomatic hernias. Emergency surgery for incarcerated or strangulated hernias. Open or laparoscopic approaches available.

OPEN INGUINAL HERNIA REPAIR: Bassini repair (historical - posterior wall reinforcement), Shouldice repair (multilayer posterior wall), Lichtenstein tension-free mesh repair (gold standard open technique). Mesh repair has lowest recurrence rate.

LAPAROSCOPIC REPAIR: TAPP (transabdominal preperitoneal) - enters peritoneal cavity, dissects preperitoneal space. TEP (totally extraperitoneal) - does not enter peritoneal cavity. Advantages: bilateral repair, reduced postoperative pain, faster recovery. Disadvantages: general anesthesia, higher cost, learning curve.

FEMORAL HERNIA REPAIR: Low approach (Lockwood), high approach (McEvedy), inguinal approach (Lotheissen). All involve opening the canal and mesh repair.

COMPLICATIONS OF REPAIR: Seroma or hematoma, wound infection, chronic pain (inguinodynia), recurrence, testicular atrophy (ischemia), nerve injury (ilioinguinal, iliohypogastric, genital branch of genitofemoral).'),
('d0000039-0000-0000-0000-000000000039'::uuid, 'clinical_pearls', 5, 'Clinical Pearls', 'Inguinal hernia is above and medial to pubic tubercle; femoral is below and lateral. Indirect hernia passes lateral to inferior epigastric vessels through deep ring. Direct hernia passes medial to inferior epigastric vessels through Hesselbach triangle. Femoral hernias have highest strangulation risk. Lichtenstein tension-free mesh repair is gold standard for open inguinal repair. Always examine opposite groin and scrotum.'),
('d0000039-0000-0000-0000-000000000039'::uuid, 'key_points', 6, 'Key Points Summary', 'Inguinal hernias are most common (75% of all hernias). Indirect inguinal is most common type overall. Direct hernias rarely strangulate. Femoral hernias have high strangulation risk and are more common in women. Lichtenstein mesh repair has lowest recurrence rate. Emergency surgery for strangulated hernia. Chronic groin pain (inguinodynia) is common complication. Hesselbach triangle: rectus, inferior epigastrics, inguinal ligament.');

